            "last_activity_date": 1579737768,
            "creation_date": 1579737768,
            "body": "<p>You could use the fully qualified class Name instead.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>a.b.c.MyClass myClass = new a.b.c.MyClass();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Also see \n<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/11907245/java-import-statement-vs-fully-qualified-name\">Java: import statement vs fully qualified name?<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 59869934,
            "question_id": 59869872
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/7ghSp.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 238684,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 507738,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/507738/mc-emperor",
                "reputation": 23306,
                "display_name": "MC Emperor",
                "accept_rate": 71
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1579739856,
            "creation_date": 1579739856,
            "body": "<p>Qualification and visibility have little to do with eachother. Those are different concepts.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Visibility<\/strong> (enforced by <em>access modifiers<\/em> like <code>public<\/code>, <code>protected<\/code>, <code>private<\/code> and <em>package-private<\/em>) is about which class may access (i.e. call or use) it.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Qualification<\/strong> is about the compiler asking you: \"Okay, you are mentioning a class name, but there could be thousands around with that name. Which one do you mean?\"<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 59870164,
            "question_id": 59869872
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4b3f47ee34523f975c2dfc2e8bb13a63?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1915670,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1728310,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1728310/user1728310",
                "reputation": 687,
                "display_name": "user1728310",
                "accept_rate": 50
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1579738282,
            "creation_date": 1579738282,
            "body": "<p>Java compiler restricts its search for classes inside the package only. In order to make use of any class belonging to a different package, you have to import it explicitly. You can read more about packages <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/package/packages.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Access specifiers are more from restricting the methods from being accessible by outside world. These access specifiers enforce further restrictions on top of what is enforced by packages. You can refer to <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/accesscontrol.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this link<\/a> for access specifiers.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 59870003,
            "question_id": 59869872
